.SH WILDCARDS
On Windows, cmd.exe and PowerShell do not expand \f[B]*\f[R] and
\f[B]?\f[R] wildcards before starting programs, so \f[B]squeeze\f[R]
expands them itself.
\f[B]squeeze *.log\f[R] works the same as in bash.
\f[B][\&...]\f[R] is matched literally (brackets are legal Windows
filename characters).
\f[B]**\f[R] is rejected with a usage error \(em use the tool\(cqs
recursive matching options instead.
A pattern that matches nothing is passed through unchanged so the normal
\(lqnot found\(rq error follows.
In cmd, quoting a pattern (e.g.\ \f[I]\(lq*.log\(rq\f[R]) suppresses
expansion.
On Linux and macOS the shell expands wildcards as usual and
\f[B]squeeze\f[R] does nothing extra.
.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Success.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
Compression or decompression error: corrupt input, truncated gzip stream
(ISIZE mismatch), multi\-member gzip (concatenated gzip is rejected \(em
see BUGS), unknown format, write failed.
.TP
\f[B]2\f[R]
Usage error: bad arguments, missing input, \f[B]\(enbrotli\f[R] with
\f[B]\(enzstd\f[R], \f[B]\(enoutput\f[R] empty/whitespace,
\f[B]\(enoutput\f[R] with multiple inputs, level out of range.
.SH BUGS
Multi\-member gzip (concatenated gzip streams produced by
\f[CR]cat a.gz b.gz\f[R] or \f[CR]gzip file1 file2 && cat *.gz\f[R]) is
rejected with exit 1 and \(lqdata is corrupt or truncated\(rq, even
though the decompressed content is correct.
This is because squeeze validates the final ISIZE field against the
cumulative decompressed byte count, and for multi\-member streams ISIZE
only represents the last member\(cqs size.
.PP
Workaround: pipe through system gzip (\f[CR]gzip \-dc concat.gz\f[R])
which handles multi\-member natively, or split the concatenation back
into individual \f[CR].gz\f[R] files.
.PP
This trade\-off was made to prefer loud false\-positives on rare
multi\-member input over silent corruption on common
incompressible\-truncation input.
A future release may add proper member\-by\-member parsing.
